Data Storage Strategy

A data storage strategy is a plan for managing and using data. It involves choosing storage options, organizing data, and ensuring backups and recovery. The goal is to keep data secure, accessible, and cost-effective.

Data Storage Overview

Explore Data Storage Strategy Goals

Click each data storage strategy goal to learn more.

The following are the benefits of the data storage strategy:

  • More secure data

  • Ensured compliance

  • Better performing applications

  • Lower costs

  • More efficient operations

  • Optimized resource utilization

  • More flexible

  • Easier scalability

Key components of data storage are storage media, storage systems, storage technologies, and data management.

The following table lists the key components of data storage with examples.

Component

Description

Examples

Storage media

Physical devices used to store data

HDDs, SSDs, optical discs, tape drive

Storage systems

Methods for organizing and accessing storage resources

DAS, NAS, SAN, cloud storage

Storage technologies

Technologies that enhance storage performance and flexibility

SDS, RAID, Flash storage, Hybrid storage

Data management

Systems and structures for managing data storage and retrieval

File systems (NTFS, ext4), DBMS (MySQL, PostgreSQL), storage virtualization

Data Storage Strategy Types

A data storage strategy for AI clusters is a detailed plan that describes how data will be stored, managed, and accessed to support AI and machine learning (ML) workloads. Considering the significant data demands of AI and ML tasks, a robust storage strategy is important for optimal performance, scalability, and efficiency. Key considerations and components that usually include a data storage strategy for AI clusters can be split into two groups: performance and scalability considerations and management and security considerations.

Performance and scalability considerations focus on optimizing the performance, scalability, and accessibility of the storage system to meet the high demands of AI and ML workloads. Considerations include the following:

  • Performance and low latency

    1. High-speed solid-state drives (SSDs), Non-Volatile Memory Express (NVMe) storage solutions, and optimized storage protocols like Remote Direct Memory Access (RDMA) over Converged Ethernet (RoCE) achieve high throughput and low latency.

  • Scalability

    1. Distributed file systems (such as HDFS) or cloud-based storage solutions (for example, Amazon S3, Google Cloud Storage) support expanding AI workloads without sacrificing performance.

  • Accessibility

    1. Shared storage solutions (such as network-attached storage [NAS] or SAN) to ensure that all nodes within the AI cluster can quickly access the required data.

  • Parallel file systems

    1. Parallel file systems enable simultaneous data access and writing by multiple processes, which boosts throughput and minimizes bottlenecks.

  • Data tiering and caching

    1. Data tiering optimizes cost and performance by moving infrequently accessed data to slower storage and retaining frequently accessed data on high-speed storage.

    2. Caching frequently used data enhances overall system performance.

  • Compatibility with AI frameworks and tools

    1. Ensure that the storage solution integrates seamlessly with AI frameworks like TensorFlow and PyTorch and tools like Kubeflow and MLflow to optimize workflow efficiency.

  • Cost efficiency

    1. Balance cost and performance with a mix of on-premises and cloud storage solutions; high-speed local SSDs for frequently accessed data and cost-effective cloud storage for archival data.

Management and security considerations address the storage system's management, security, and reliability aspects to ensure data protection and effective handling. Considerations include the following:

  • Security and compliance

    1. Implement encryption, access control, and regular audits to protect sensitive data and comply with regulatory requirements.

  • Data durability and reliability

    1. Redundant storage solutions, regular backups, and fault-tolerant systems protect valuable data and prevent loss from hardware failures.

  • Software-defined storage (SDS)

    1. SDS solutions for flexibility and simplified management abstract storage hardware and present it as a unified pool of resources, which allow for management and automation through software.

Each group addresses different but complementary aspects of a comprehensive data storage strategy, ensuring that performance needs and management requirements are met.

In practice, a data storage strategy for AI clusters typically involves a combination of on-premises high-performance storage for handling active workloads, cloud storage for scalability and flexibility, and archival storage for long-term data retention. This approach allows organizations to balance the need for speed and responsiveness with the ability to scale and manage costs effectively.

On-premises storage provides the low-latency access that is required for real-time data processing and high-performance computing tasks. Cloud storage offers the scalability that is needed to accommodate growing data volumes and provides flexibility in managing data across different geographical locations. Archival storage securely retains historical data that may be infrequently accessed but is still valuable for compliance, research, or future analysis.

The specific strategy should be tailored to your organization’s unique requirements, including the nature of the AI workloads, budget constraints, and long-term data management goals. Consider factors such as data access patterns, the importance of data durability, and integration with existing systems. By using this multitiered storage approach, organizations can ensure that their AI infrastructure is robust and adaptable for meeting current and future data management needs.

Data Storage Strategy Management

Data storage systems are not easy to manage. Data must be easy to access but stored securely to protect against human errors, malicious attacks, and machine failures.

The following list includes some good practices that help you manage your data storage strategy more efficiently:

  • Storage resource management (SRM) applications: SRMs are especially useful in large, multivendor environments, to ensure that the components are operating efficiently, and capacity is not wasted.

  • System consolidation: Managing storage becomes more complicated as more storage systems are added to handle increased capacity needs. Instead of replacing existing systems with larger ones, it is often easier to add new units. However, managing many separate systems, especially NAS systems that handle rapidly increasing file data, can be difficult. Consolidating multiple storage systems into a larger unit simplifies management but may require investing in tools or services to move data, especially if systems are from different vendors.

  • Storage tiering: Storage tiering involves categorizing data based on its importance to the company and storing it on appropriate types of storage. Less critical data can reside on slower and cheaper disk systems, while crucial and frequently accessed data is stored on fast SSDs. This approach simplifies data management and ensures that different types of data receive appropriate levels of protection.

  • Strategic SSD deployment: One of the trickiest challenges in storage management is optimizing a storage array for peak performance. Traditionally, techniques like short-stroking were used to boost performance from disk-based systems by focusing on the fastest parts of hard drives. However, this method was complex to manage and inefficient in terms of disk space. A more effective solution today is to strategically integrate SSDs into the array for high-performance applications. Despite SSDs being more costly than traditional disks, their targeted deployment can streamline performance management and potentially reduce costs over time.

  • Hybrid cloud storage: Using cloud storage helps reduce on-site storage needs and eases management. Data that is stored in the cloud requires minimal oversight and virtually no management effort. By shifting less-used and less-critical data to the cloud, storage administrators can concentrate on higher priority data that needs fast access and robust storage solutions.

  • Opt for scale-out storage systems: Choosing a scale-out storage system can simplify managing your storage environment. Unlike scale-up systems, which cannot add controllers as capacity grows, scale-out arrays allow administrators to add both, capacity and controllers. This capability helps maintain performance levels as the storage needs of the company expand.

  • Maximize the efficiency of virtual machine utilization: Server virtualization allows easy creation of virtual machines (VMs), but this situation can lead to many unused or abandoned VMs, which are also known as orphaned VMs. These VMs still occupy storage and increase management efforts, especially for data protection tasks.

    To address this issue, administrators can use tools like vCenter for VMware or scripts for Hyper-V and other virtual server environments to identify and remove orphaned VMs efficiently. This approach helps streamline data center operations and reduces unnecessary storage usage.
